  "final_analysis": "The management of hyperthyroidism during pregnancy, particularly in the first trimester, requires careful consideration of the safety profiles of available medications. Methimazole and Carbimazole (which is converted to Methimazole in the body) are associated with higher risks of teratogenic effects, such as congenital malformations, when used during the first trimester. Propylthiouracil, on the other hand, is generally considered safer for use during the first trimester due to its lower risk of causing birth defects compared to Methimazole. Perchlorate is not commonly used as a first-line treatment due to its lower efficacy and limited data on safety in pregnancy. Based on standard medical guidelines and consensus, Propylthiouracil is the preferred choice for treating hyperthyroidism in the first trimester of pregnancy. This aligns with the enhanced information provided, which supports the use of Propylthiouracil due to its safety profile.",
